b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZ=
jNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjAyMzc2MH0/0b486fb9a893ce5f026c924764=
a63cece91f727fbfb3271571f5f91e69d55838" style=3D"text-decoration: underline=
; color: #d40000;">first</a> with this news.) The deal will run for at leas=
t two years and involve a modest rights fee. Fox will carry LIV events on i=
ts broadcast network and cable channels, while LIV will produce the events,=
 taking a big expense off the network=E2=80=99s plate. I expect the deal wi=
ll include some sort of commitment for LIV sponsors to buy ad time during t=
he telecasts=E2=80=94a common practice known as =E2=80=9Cunderpinning.=E2=
=80=9D<br/><br/>Back in January of 2023, the CW
signed a deal to carry LIV events as a way to build out its sports portfoli=
o. The network has since signed deals to carry college football and basketb=
all games, plus <em>WWE NXT</em>, but declined its option to extend the LIV=
 deal another year. Fox wasn=E2=80=99t sniffing around for LIV in 2023, but=
 the industry gossip suggests that a master plan is afoot here. LIV is owne=
d by Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Public Investment Fund (PIF). Saudi Arabia, of =
course, is the site of the 2034 World Cup. And Fox, <em>of course</em>, is =
in the market to acquire the rights to the 2030 and 2034 World Cups=E2=80=
=A6</li>
